# H O R A P O L L O.

#### ΒΙΒΛΙΟΝ ΠΡΟΩΤΟΝ·

#### BOOK I.

### I. HOW THEY DENOTE ETERNITY.

<span id="img_00500"></span> ![](img/00500.jpg) <span
id="fr_1"></span>[1](#fn_1.md)

To denote Eternity <span id="fr_2"></span>[2](#fn_2.md) they depict the SUN
and MOON, because their elements are eternal. But when they would
represent Eternity <span id="fr_3"></span>[2](#fn_2.md) differently,

<span id="page_6">p. 6</span>

they delineate a SERPENT with its tail covered by the rest of its body:
the Egyptians call this Ouraius, <span id="fr_4"></span>[1](#fn_3.md) which
in the Greek language signifies Basilisk: <span
id="fr_5"></span>[2](#fn_4.md) And they place golden figures of it round
the Gods. The Egyptians say that Eternity is represented by this animal;
because of the three existing species of serpents, the others are
mortal, but this alone is immortal; and <span
id="fr_6"></span>[3](#fn_6.md) because it destroys any other animal by
merely breathing upon <span id="fr_7"></span>[4](#fn_5.md) it even without
biting. And hence, inasmuch as it thus appears to have power over life
and death, they place it upon the head of the Gods.

